Problem and Data

This notebook is an attempt at training a neural network to classify images of human cell samples as either cancerous or not. The data comes from Kaggle which hosted it as part of a competition to build a predictive model 

Data Source: https://www.kaggle.com/c/histopathologic-cancer-detection/data
    
The images were supplied as .tiff images 96 x 96 pixels in 3 layers to account for color. There are 220,025 training images which are preclassified (0 non-cancerous, 1 cancerous) according to an accompanying csv file with labels. There are 57,458 images in the test folder which do not have labels and instead require a submission to kaggle in order to validate.

Data Cleaning

Data cleaning in this project consisted primarily of reformatting the data and data storage into a format that keras was more familiar with.

Format of images

The Keras method, image_dataset_from_directory, does not accept .tiff files so Pillow python module was used to convert all of the files from .tiff to .bmp. Bmp was chosen because it does not lose any of the resolution from the images and is compatible with keras.

Data storage

Keras expects the data to be stored in separate folders, each folder name matching the label of the data. Supposedly keras can be fed the labels as a list, but after many hours I was unable to discover the correct way to do this so it was easier to use a one time script to read the labels csv file and move the images into separate folders based on their labels.

Building the model

For simplicity I chose a Sequential model with 10 layers.

1. The Rescaling layer normalizes the RGB values into 0-1 range which helps with convergence during training.

2. The Conv2D is a convolutional layer with 16 filters. This is an attempt to find some of the smaller patterns and features in the images. There is padding to prevent any downscaling of the image at this stage.

3. MaxPooling2D layer explicitly down samples the input to reduce the size of the image for later layers to process.

4. and 5. Another set of layers of convolution and max pooling. These layers pull out some of the larger features and further reduce the size for the last layer. There are 32 filters in this Conv layer.

6. and 7. A final set of filters to learn the more complex features of the images. There are 64 filters in this layer.

8. Flatten reduces the output from the last layer into a 1D vector which can be fed into the Dense, fully connected layer.

9. Dense has 128 neurons which are all fully connected to the output from the Flatten layer and the final Dense layer. This layer helps pull out some of the non-linear connections between the features.

10. Dense final layer outputs probabilites for each of the two data classes and serves as the final arbiter of the classification.

In[7]:
model = Sequential([
  Rescaling(1./255, input_shape=(img_height, img_width, 3)),
  Conv2D(16, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  MaxPooling2D(),
  Conv2D(32, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  MaxPooling2D(),
  Conv2D(64, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  MaxPooling2D(),
  Flatten(),
  Dense(128, activation='relu'),
  Dense(num_classes)
])
In[8]:
model.compile(optimizer='adam',
              loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

Software environment

Initial training showed that a task this large, training on 220,000 images through a large neural network demonstrated that the CPU on this laptop was not up to the task to complete the training in under 8 hours per run.

In order to utilize the GPU, I set up a tensoflow environment. The newer tensor flow versions no longer support GPU usage on native Windows so I created a WSL conda environment running this notebook with linux.

Utilizing the GPU reduced the runtime from over 10 minutes per epoch to under 3 minutes each with an average close to 2 minutes.

Train model

Early attempts at training failed with a batch size of 32 and 16 due to memory constraints. The laptop I am using has 64 GB of RAM, but it ran out. I brought the batch size down to 8 in order to get around these constraints while I needed to use the laptop for other purposes.

Refactor the training model

The model quickly overfit by epoch 3 and validation accuracy didn't improve after that. In order to reduce the learning rate, I added dropout layers to each of the convolutional layers.

In[14]:
model = Sequential([
  Rescaling(1./255, input_shape=(img_height, img_width, 3)),
  Conv2D(16, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  MaxPooling2D(),
  Dropout(rate=0.25),
  Conv2D(32, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  MaxPooling2D(),
  Dropout(rate=0.25),
  Conv2D(64, 3, padding='same', activation='relu'),
  MaxPooling2D(),
  Flatten(),
  Dense(128, activation='relu'),
  Dropout(rate=0.25),
  Dense(num_classes)
])
In[15]:
model.compile(optimizer='adam',
              loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

Choosing the final model

Both check points 12 and 17 performed relatviely the same as far as validation loss was concerned and I was curious if it would be better to use the earlier model in case there was overfitting coming from the extra 5 epochs run. I decided to submit both to kaggle in an effort to determine the best model.

In[40]:
# Load the best model from the checkpoints
model = load_model('./checkpoints_02/weights-12-0.22.hdf5')
In[51]:
# Make predictions using the trained model
test_steps = np.ceil(len(test_ds) / batch_size)
predictions = model.predict(test_ds)

# Get the class labels
predicted_classes = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)

# Save the predictions to a CSV file
filenames = test_ds.file_paths

results = pd.DataFrame({'filepaths': filenames, 'label': predicted_classes})
results['id'] = results['filepaths'].apply(lambda x: os.path.splitext(os.path.basename(x))[0])
results = results[['id','label']]
results.to_csv('test_predictions.csv', index=False)

Conclusions

Overall I think it was an interesting exercise. I certainly struggled with getting my computer to run such a large scale model far more than I did creating and running the model itself. One of the frustrating things in Data Science is how fast everything moves along so any online tutorial or example code is already using deprecated methods by the time it is published. The model itself could probably do a lot better than 87% accuracy given time to dive into other layers or more complicated structures. One thing I would like to try is find a way to generate images from the intermediate steps to see what the model might be pulling out of the images at each layer.

I was encouraged that the dropout layer did seem to help a bit with overfitting and that it really slowed down the learning rate. Prior to the dropout layers, the validation loss peaked fast at epoch 5 and then didn't improve.

One other thing I would be curious to try as researcher is to see how consistent the predictions are on a per patient basis, vs per sample. If we could know that some set of samples came from patients who were positive for cancer, but not all the images were of the cancer, would the model be able to correctly predict enough of the positive images that this kind of analysis became overwhelming? For example, maybe a single image prediction is only accurate to 95% but a group of images from the same patient would boost the accuracy to 99.9% based on the summation of the individual images predicted. Maybe this type of approach wouldn't work, but I would be curious to attempt it.
